11. 19, 20. Damnatus longi . . . laboris. Damnare governs an acc. of the person, a genitive of the charge or penalty. So damnatus venefici, ‘condemned on a charge of poisoning ’; damnatus capitale, ‘ condemned to lose the caput or civic existence ’; damnatus octupli, ‘ condemned to pay eight times the amount’ in question. The abl. is also found in both senses, e. g. capite. Of these constructions, the ablative should be related to the abl. of price, the genitive to the gen. aster verbs of estimating.
